Backcountry Navigator is the real deal for adventuring / mountain sports.
have used it a few times and really like it..takes some learning to get around with what the button symbols are but has good instructions.
Works as promised and allows for easy caching of maps offline. User experience and GUI have been greatly enhanced over the last year's updates although it still does have a dated feel to it.
this app is awesome it has everything you'll need and then some. I have a lot of GPS systems but this is my favorite.
Day hike in Colorado as a hobby whenever I am in the state. Love to turn on my BackCountry Navigator and track the trip. Easy to use and records great information.

I use this at work laying out natural gas pipelines.  I use it when out of town with my family to look around areas where we stay.  I love the access to multiple map sources.  I use Google Nexus 7" v1.

Before I got this app, I purchased a Garmin ETrex 20 for about $160.  The ETrex is a great improvement over my 15 year old Garmin GPS III, especially because you can download free topo maps into it from GPS File Depot.  I found, though, that the small screen on the Etrex was frustrating to use at times if one has experience using large paper topo maps, which also have their drawbacks.  On an impulse, I recently purchased a reconditioned Nexus 7 tablet for $110 and when it arrived in the mail I downloaded the Back Country App into it.  I am now wondering if I should have purchased the ETrex.  As other reviewers have mentioned, the app interface is a bit intimidating.  So far I have spent roughly 90 minutes learning how to navigate the various menus.  That may seem like a long time, but after you spend some time learning the interface and then using the app, you begin to see what a powerful and flexible app it is.  It has many, many advantages over the Etrex.  If you have a Android tablet with GPS, seriously consider checking this app out before buying a dedicated GPS unit.  It is worth every penny and then some.
Works as advertised.  Great!

Just returned from a 45 mile of the JMT and loved the BC Nav Pro app.  I had populated the map with known campsites before the trip and it was incredibly convenient to be able to plan a night's stay without searching for a flat campsite.  My only request would be to be able to input waypoints on a PC and have them sync with my Samsung Galaxy.

My Galaxy S5 Active has all the features of a dedicated hand held/hiking GPS, and a much bigger screen.  Extra cost topo maps have all the trails I use, so far.  Galaxy's bright screen can be zoomed and read in bright daylight.  GPS turns on and locates current position in just a few moments.  Love this software and my new phone!
Perfect for me when hiking local, short trails.
Great for backcountry wanderings.  They don't follow Android interface conventions, so it takes a little longer to learn.
replyContent: Which Android interface conventions do you believe we are violating? Please write to the helpdesk. Perhaps we can remedy it.

content: This is the best app for hunters, hikers, anything outdoor.  I use it for hunting.  While scouting I trace my route, mark when I see "game" after days/weeks of scouting it's very easy to review prone location for the game I'm hunting.  10 stars easy!
Its just s great app for downloading maps for back country navigation. Just plan ahead when going on long trips. Been using it for a over year with no problems
Awesome app
very nice would recommend to a friend

I spend a lot of time outdoors, some of that time I am miles from service.  It has been great having GPS functionality on my phone!  I don't even carry my Garmin anymore (if you plan of using this app don't forget to download maps before you leave service area)
Subscriptions can get spendy
I have the iPhone and android. GPS kit is the best for Apple BUT this one is the best for android. I'm a State Park Ranger!

I have been doing the smartphone thing since around 2007. I would say I am moderately techy and vastly outdoorsy.  This app is simply amazing and is the only app I endorse to all my friends. Love it!!!!!!! If you like to be outdoors and do things adventurous or not, you need this App. I have had it since 2010 or so.
Amazing backcountry GPS software with excellent maps and ability to store maps offline. Money well spent.
If you need offline Top Maps that work when you only have a GPS signal this is your solution.

I wouldn't dream of venturing in the backcountry without this helpful tool. While nothing truly beats an old school map when you're away from a charging outlet... This is easily the next best thing to radical backcountry navigation.
Used it in the UK; USA, white mountains NH and Vermont and in Canada (Montreal). Worked perfectly.
Couldn't be more pleased.this app is the best one I have ever used for trail riding.
Exellent mapping tool, great for off road navigation.
I have tested and used this app alongside a garmin montana and it works fantastic. Extra points to cal topo for a spectacular mapping program.
Dam good app
Best offline backcountry topo mapper since my N800 and Maemo Mapper! I love that I can attach photos to waypoints. I used the Bluetooth GPS app to use my external GPS and save my phone's batteries.
Does what it's supposed to do.
I use Backcountry Navigator on backpack and mountain bike trips.  The best I've tried!

Best GPS app I've downloaded yet. There was some connectivity problems while on satellite only, however there was heavy cloud cover. Just some tiles on map that said "no connectivity" Hope to try again this weekend in same area. Thank you!
replyContent:
We don't get internet over satellite.
Make sure you download the areas at home first according to the instructions.

content: Never lets me down. In the middle of the Sante Fe national Forest yesterday and my dad had his GPSr. This has access to better maps and is easier to use on the fly. Love it.
Just used it again on a 6 day wilderness trip on Sequoia National Park.  Worked perfectly.
Great for military FTX
Essential and easy use during  a week long off the grid  expedition in the Rockies.  Paper back up advised though,  this app can't help you if you drop your phone down a crevice...
Worked awesome on my week long hunting trip. Out of the service area. They seem to have worked out all the glitches  I was having earlier.
replyContent: Glad it worked! Hope your hunt was successful.

content: Great app. Super nice to have in the woods.

I usually do off trail multi point backpacking and I don't do it without this app. This app actually saved me a few times from certain peril. And helped me find amazing places you don't see in publications. Everything works as it says it does which is saying a lot for an app now a days. Thank you for putting out a quality product!
Love it this is the only GPS I use now
Best best best

I just got back from an adventure riding trip on my dual sport.  It is fast and easy to use especially for the amount of work it does.  During the trip it worked flawlessly and navigated us through some serious terrain.  Thank you for all the hard work the team have put in to make this happen.  This week I planned our next trip route right from my phone. Links great with google earth. The help team are fast and responsive if you have any issues. This is by far the best app I own.

I rarely rate apps. This one is special because it truly makes my Android phone like a Handheld GPS Plus. The ability to download maps and have everything work on airplane mode is the best feature. Fantastic.
Best mapping app for backpacking

Great update! I'm on galaxy s5. It's outstanding. I hike away from cell service, so i downloaded the maps, i did not even read the instructions,  (although I do like the "tip" screens that come up now, though I turned most off, I keep the ones for less used areas on)  It doesn't drain my battery. I use this three days a week.  I abandoned my normal GPS device.  A brain dead monkey could add way points. Easy. Works. Great map selection. TERRIFIC support when I've emailed for things. Great job
Have been using this APP for a couple of years and find it an excellent tool for off track navigation in the New Zealand bush. Also excellent help and support for new features.

Used it for my 2011 AT Thru-hike. Excellent product,  off-line worked great. No data connection, no problem. Tried the demo version (30 days) and found it worked so well I was happy to upgrade to the pro version after 20 days.

I've been using this app for a few years and it keeps getting better. The ability to preload map tiles before heading into the woods to find a summit is a huge plus. I've also been using the track functions to create .kml files.  I'm an amateur radio operator and participate in a Summits on the Air program. This requires we find our way to specific summits for our 'activations'. BCN's ability to preload map tiles, along with better topo maps than in my Garmin, really make a difference. I wouldn't hit the trail without it (and a spare battery for my phone)!  It gets four stars because it is somewhat confusing and/or difficult to learn. Admittedly it does a lot in a small space but many of the features are tough to understand. It is worth the effort though, the results more than make up for the learning curve.  Jim/KK1W
Back Country Navigator
Threw out my GPS and just use this great app backpacking in the Adirondacks.
Great support. Engaged developer.

I have gone through this app trying it out against several other competitors.  All have their pluses and negatives.  This app is nice enough although I find it a bit of a pain to look up maps compared to other apps.  As far as hiking trails it lags behind a little unless you fork up the money for Accuterra maps which are awesome if you can afford it... I couldn't. Maps are just OK and similar quality to others accept they did  NOT show hiking trails very well at all. Overall a decent APP but would be great if they made switching maps easier  and included Accuterra maps at a much cheaper price.
replyContent:
You CAN view the paid maps in a trial. You are offered a one week trial for Digital Globe and a two week trial for accuterra. 
Besides that, there are preview websites available. See gpstopomaps.com and gpstopomaps.com/digitalglobe/.

content: Thanks for the great app. I don't buy many apps but this one is great. It has a bit of a learning curve but once it's figured out, it's awesome. Thanks again!

I used it hunting. Great gps tracking capabilities and the digital tracking cookies help you to track your progress and assist in back tracking if you get stuck on a trail. It is best that you download the map data before you hit the trails. I highly recommend it.

Just installed it on my phone (Galaxy S3) and tablet (Sony Xperia). On holiday in Wales now and enjoyed the detailed OS maps during our first walk ( without extra charge, all this for less than the price of one paper map!)  The free 'world topo maps' are great too, and show good details where I live (The Netherlands).   Very Happy so far and exploring the more advanced features (like importing downloaded tracks)
This app is getting better and better. It was not much chop in Australia due to lack of maps now at least we have in NSW the SIX maps.  It would be really good if it accepted the GARMIN TOPO maps.
For hunters, fisherman and hikers this app is an absolute must have. The UI could use a little work to make it easier to use, but it works fine once you learn how to use it correctly.
Requires a little learning to use but worked flawlessly without a data connection to mark way points on my hike using my Samsung Galaxy S5!

A great app. Have not used it that much, but from my humble start I've found it a better system than trying to use my normal Garmin car gps (with DL'd topo maps)  for topo's and trail riding. I can't wait to start really using this in Natl. Parks.  So far no issues with my S5, it's fast and smooth, and it will be very useful I can tell already.  Thank You developers !  Allan
Best app for the wilderness.

I've used BCN for several years in the UK and Europe, its a fantastic way of always having offline maps available on your android phone, you just download the areas of map you require prior to travelling from the selection of different map sources available then you have it when you need it regardless of phone signal by using the phones GPS fantastic. I wouldn't be without BCN
A great tool for hunting, hiking and offroading, or just wandering around.
Love it.
Awesome maps. Must have for  techy outdoorsmen!
Best $10 I ever spent!

Worth the money to go pro. Been great on family walks and cycling.  I used to use multimap until they stopped allowing me to use my previously purchased maps. No cheeky multimap download quota subscription with this.
WOW
Loved the app
I use this app all the time. What more can I say.
Great GPS app!
Great backpacking tool

Great app.  Saved my butt more than once after getting turned around in the swamp.  Had a problem installing an update yesterday and contacted the help desk.  Got a very quick response with the solution having to do with the Play store, not the app (I knew it couldn't be the app, since the app has only ever worked great!).
I have had this app for years. I use it to track new trails while I'm off roading. I have told all my friend's about it and have sent them pictures of trails.

We use BCN (on a Samsung S4) extensively throughout California, and usually just leave our old Garmin in the pack.  BCN is just terrific ... has saved our butts several times.  $11.99 is dirt cheap. This is not just an "app" ... it is serious software.   We use it not only for serious mointaineering (6 summits of Mt. WHITNEY with BCN), but also use it for short hikes in San Diego's many canyons in the city's extensive urban park system.  Great software !
Great app
Really awesome
Please change the intrusive help screens.
replyContent: Just check them off, or turn them all off in settings->Display.

content: I use this app when hiking the Finger Lakes Trail in upstate New York. Imported the FLT gpx map files before setting out. No more getting lost! Most of the trails are well marked. But sometimes you miss a trail marker and you get off track. This app shows me where I am in relation to the trail and gets me back on the trail.
Hope SD storage gets fixed
replyContent: For months now, we have posted this information: goo.gl/rb727h

content: Had some drama with last Android update I think. Working perfectly again. Great tech assistance from Nathan and Dan.
replyContent: Glad you got it working again.

content: I have used this all around the world to find my way.  I just took it to Glacier National Park for the USGS Topo maps and it was awesome.  I used it last month in Jordan for the OpenCycleMap street maps.  It is an essential tool for any outdoor activities!
I use the app for alpine climbing and it has saved me from taking many vertical feet going in the wrong direction. Love the frequent updates.

replyContent: I'm sorry that you did not receive a response back in Nov '12. We cannot tell who you are from this message, so if you would like to talk more about ATV trails please contact the helpdesk.

content: I have been using GPS's since they were first made available to the public. I am a professional scenic photographer and this ap is very accurate and useful while in the deep back country. I have used several brands of hand held gps's and this application competes and kicks butt when doing comparisons to $400 & $600 units. Their tech support is by far the best I have encountered. Worth the investment.

My only want is for a companion program for the PC. I have a hard time selecting maps on the small screen--I use atlases made with MOBAC instead. It's OK to work with exported gpx and kmls. Would be nicer to work with native data on PC, especially with photos and notes attached to waypoints.
A New Zealand user using it for bush walks in local (Northland area). Recommended
Have used this in many countries, always excellent.
Use it all the time. Surpurb app.!!!
Fast and responsive unlike many other GPS apps with offline maps around. Would like to be able to select map to download even on bigger zoom (ie 9), but understand limitations.
replyContent: You have received a response. I have record of a response to you on June 19th. Check your email filters. As I said then, Some storage mechanisms are extremely inefficient at storing a whole bunch of tiny little files. For that reason, choose a map package. This crams all the tiles into a few big files.

content: Isn't every thing I want, but close enough for me.
Works perfectly on my nexus7 and my desire hd now on my S4 don't down rate until you contact the Dev

content: Great app !

I probably don't use half of the available features, but what I do use it for mountain bike exploring thru Mt Hood and finding new camp spots it's great!  The US Forestry map is what I use the most.  The Foresty maps are clear and they allow me to zoom in.  Before I head out, I download the areas and I'm set.  I went from using a Samsung Galaxy II to a 4.  The II had a hard time locking on to the GPS not so with the 4.  Backcountry Navigator has been a great product and I was happy to pay to upgrade to the Pro version.

Motorola Moto X. This app is fantastic. I recently took a 600 mile, mostly off road, motorcycle trip through the Great Smoky Mountains using this app as my primary nav. I made the route on google maps, and it was super easy to transfer the entire route onto backcountry navigator, where it displayed perfectly. content: Great app for Moto

Threw both my frustrating, expensive GPSs (you know who they are!) in the garbage ... "Colorado Joe" they call me! I'm in the mountains every week & weekend. I live at Tahoe and am hiking or backcountry skiing year round. As such I use Backcountry navigator on a daily basis. It has totally displaced my garmin for daily use. I still take my garmin along for extended trips due to its superior ruggedness, but I greatly prefer the simplicity, the fact that I dont' need another device, the availability of maps (and navigational charts), and the larger screen.  It is a great app and I recommend it to everyone.

On Southwest trip BCN helped me out 2 times.  First, I was crossing the Hopi reservation in Arizona and had to camp in the middle of the night.  I was told to camp at the Hopi Cultural Center, but couldn't find it.  I opened up BCN with the Arizona vector map loaded, displayed my GPS location, expanded the view, and I found the Hopi Cultural Center building labelled on the map!  I was only a few miles away. The other time, I was on a trail in Canyonlands Islands National Park.  I thought I was on the correct trail to False Kiva, but the trail took me to the edge of a cliff.  I got out BCN with the Utah vector map loaded, got my GPS location, found the trail I was on, and also found, just a short distance away, the correct trail. The vector maps are great, as indicated above.  Download the whole state in one shot and have incredible detail for cities, streets, trails, ...

BCN was helpful on the tour bus. I knew where I was and about long to my next destination. I got lost walking back from the Jerusalem museums and used BCN to find my  way back to the hotel.  One problem was that the sun was so bright I had difficulty reading the display.

I have been using BNP for several years and have enjoyed it's ease of use and the variety of maps that are available.  Several of my friends have added it to their Android phones and those with iPhones are jealous.  April 2014; upon getting my new Android phone, I was surprised to see that Back Country Pro was ready to use.  I was afraid I'd have to buy it again..

Can't you bundle these somehow and archive/compress the bundles to take up less space in fewer files?
replyContent: Yes, you can by using map packages. You only have to choose a named folder when you download and they will all be crammed into a few large files.

content: Works described and user friendly. A lot of data formats available.

I love this app. It is great for all my field data collection and casual hiking. There is just one (HUGE) problem. Certain agencies, such as the Utah Geological Survey, require data collection in NAD83. This application uses either WGS84 or NAD27, neither of which are equivalent to NAD83. NAD83 is also the preferred datum for federal agencies. All of my permit work will need to be converted out of NAD27 into NAD83 for my year-end reports which adds extra work for me. Honestly this is the first GPS that I have ever seen that does not come standard with NAD83 installed as a datum. I would even buy the NAD83 datum as an add-on pack! Why isn't this basic datum that is widely used available? I have knocked off 2 stars for this huge oversight. Otherwise this application is amazing. My hiking friends love it. My fellow scientists aren't as thrilled.
replyContent: Robert, the differences between WGS84 and NAD83 are less than the precision of GPS in modern day Smartphones. I would be happy to discuss this with you if you feel it ruins the app, but I have no record of a message from you.

content: Easy to use. You can go hi king wondering what you will see, rather than eva worrying where you are. I love that you can download maps of anywhere.

I use it on airplane mode when I'm off the grid and helps with the battery life too. The Best 10 bucks spent. Would have paid more! Thanks Developer you rock! replyContent:
Kevin, it is Android and Samsung that made the decision to block third party apps from the external card. It is a system permission that we can't alter but you can change it with root. See our helpdesk discussion. 
There are articles that suggest that "developers just need to update their apps for Kitkat" but they are wrong.

content: If they don't have it you don't need it.  Thanks for being there all these years.

tools that I’ve used in over 40 years of hiking and driving in remote areas of the Southwest US.  Much of my current back country navigation involves driving 4WD trucks for servicing widely dispersed emergency water stations intended to reduce deaths of migrants in the desert.  At considerably lower cost, BCN provides many of the functions of a dedicated consumer grade GPS receiver with mapping capability.  I think BCN would would still be a bargain at an even higher price that might allow the developer to expand the functionality.  The learning curve is significant, but beginners can get a lot of guidance from the online Manual, HelpDesk, and Forums.  The developer is very responsive to suggestions offered on the online Feature Request.   Some have criticized BCN’s internal capabilities for renaming and managing files containing downloaded map packages, tracks, and waypoints.  Those functions can, however, be handled with conventional file manager Apps such as Files, FX, etc.  My only complaint is that there’s no way to disable double click zoom, which becomes a problem when panning the map with trembling fingers on a bumpy road.

We like trail walking/cycling and here in the UK we're blessed with innumerable rights-of-ways, bridleways, cycle routes and other tracks, all of which and more (contours etc.) are shown on the Ordinance Survey's 1:25000 Explorer series of maps. With the OS Mapfinder app it costs £1.99 to download a 100 sq.km. tile (roughly 6x6 miles), so for the South of England from Ramsgate to Land's End up to Colchester/Gloucester it would cost around £1,000! With this app however, I downloaded those same maps for no cost at all onto my SD Card, which I can't do with Mapfinder. Also, with Mapfinder I'd have had to buy and download each tile individually (500 transactions!), whereas with this app I simply marked the areas I wanted and pressed Download. Further, whereas Mapfinder takes a whopping 96 seconds on my fast Galaxy 10.1 2 014 tablet to draw a single downloaded tile,  I can scroll across multiple tiles in this app with no lag at all. Now, add in tracking, waypoint navigation, a compass, route sharing and route analysis functions and it's a no-brainer. content: Learned it, used it, loved it.

I recently carted my DroidX around the White Clouds of Idaho and Backcountry Navigator kindof sucks.  Problem 1 - No offline help. None. Nadda. Zip. So you better have memorized everything before you head into the backcountry because backcountry navigator pro only has ONLINE help.  Problem 2 - Code design problem. The app uses SQLite, which is fine. Database is in App data space and your maps are on the SD card space. If you clear data on the App because it is acting wonky, you lose the database. The App code doesn't know either how to write out the database or rebuild itself. So you are basically hosed. This is a really, really fundamental code boo-boo.  Problem 3 - Code design problem. If you can't get a GPS fix after a couple minutes, what should you do? Keep running until the battery dies? Or alert the user? If the software interface to the GPS service is hung, what should you do? Keep wasting battery or alert the user? BCN isn't smart enough to alert the user. Instead it simply runs the battery dead. Very, very poor design for offline use.  Is Backcountry navigator worth the hype? Nope. It's not ready for serious offline use. And why do I see AdWhirl when I paid $10?
replyContent: The database is not in the app space. Thank you for the other feedback.

The Backcountry Navigator program includes a setting for "Map Magnification" with three settings, 0, 1, and 3.  On my Nexus 7, choosing 2 or 3 causes serious pixelation of the Canadian Toporama map images and switches contour intervals from 100 feet to 100 meters at map scales less detailed than level 16.  Make sure that you initially set Map Magnification at zero.  If you don't, you may be fooled into thinking that the map data is poorer quality than it is.  If you can't read labels on your machine, you might benefit from Map Magnification, but don't turn it on unless you have to.   I give the software 4/5 because for Canadians at least, the detail of available mapping could be better, and the Map Magnification function could be re-labeled somehow to avoid the confusion I had.  Crittermap staff were promptly responsive to my initial concerns, and worked with me constructively to sort out the problems I was having with map data.  Hats off to them for helpful and constructive attitude, and for producing some very useful software.
replyContent: Canadians take heart. There will be at least one new map source to try soon. We are able to scale up to higher levels when you download at 15. Watch out for the "map magnification" setting that looks tempting, but you probably don't want it.

replyContent: Were you reviewing a different app? We do NOT charge people by state or county. You can download maps for Appalachian trail for free; I can show you how. We do have many map sources and most are from the USGS.

Update 3/22/13: Just got back from another hike with this.  Compass kept swapping 90 or 180 degrees; it's useless.  Trip data was shown on the screen during most of the trip, but then disappeared again near the end of the hike.  According to Google Play, I was the first Nexus 7 user to write a review, not one of "thousands".  They can't expect more than one star for performance like this.

Its not just a cycle map. Most hiking trails are loaded into it. Love the new "beta" part to upload with everytrail. Please make  that stay. Also to get maps offline is easy with this app. No special software. Just highlight and save when you are in a WiFi area or have a connection. Great work on this!!!

I am a hiker/mountaineer that regularly does 15-25 mile day hikes and peak bagging.  I've downloaded most of the apps available for topographic navigation, and BackCountry Navigator Pro is the best hands-down.  Pay the extra $20 and get unlimited use of AccuTerra maps - they are the best out there.  You can download the maps over wifi while at home, and then put your phone into airplane mode in the backcountry.  I have an extended battery on a Droid Charge, and I can record a track for 14+ hours on a single charge if it is in airplane mode.  If you need more battery time or are on a multi-day hike, get a GoalZero solar charger with 1 or 2 battery packs.  I have used BackCountry Navigator in the winter time where I am blazing trail using a stored gpx file, and I have only experienced one time in the Palisades where it wasn't accurate.  A fellow hiker with a Garmin also couldn't get his to track correctly at that time, so there was something weird going on with the satellite signals.  I give this app 5 stars and I'm looking forward to seeing any enhancements they'll be making in the future.

I LOVE this app!  As anyone who's done it knows, snowmobiling can be dangerous even if you use all the needed safety gear and are a responsible rider.  Last weekend my family and I were high in the rockies of Colorado on one of our many sled trips when my son crashed.  He's ok and did exactly the right thing by jumping off the sled when things went bad.  But, since the sled went over the edge of the mountainside, I needed a way to recover it later because we were running out of dayligh.  With Navigator Pro on my phone, it didn't matter that we had no cell signal, it WORKED PERFECTLY!  We had been tracking our trip and after the crash, I simply marked a way point for the crash site and went back to recover the sled with some buddies.  THANK YOU for such an awesome app!  LOVE IT!
Very nice. I used other app but not as good as this. Especially the ability to view maps from different sources and the map downloading feature.

I use Backcountry Navigator Pro while offroading in the Rocky Mountains.  I love the ability to load Garmin files and Google waypoints of the trails.  The stats are particularly helpful in showing elevation, length of trip, etc.  I've recommended this product to all of my friends and will continue to do so.

Have been with GPS since it has come out and have had a number of GPS units. Great features with this app. Would stack up with my Garmin if my tablet was waterproof and less prone to damage while backpacking. Well thought out. Responsive to user requests.

I have no substantive complaints about this app.  It does what I want it to do - it provides me with topo base maps when I am in the wilds of the Wind River Range in Wyoming with no cell coverage, and I can easily record a track or waypoint anywhere that I am, including Mexico where I am now.  I also like to be able to export to my laptop, which the app does.  I use it in a Samsung Galaxy 5" media player with 750,000 map tiles that I have downloaded for anywhere I hike in my area of Wyoming, Idaho, Utah, and Montana.  I just bring along extra battery backup for the Galaxy, and I have all the GPS I need when I go on a hike or fishing.  The Galaxy also talks to my inReach satcom device for emergency communications in the field from ANYWHERE.  BackCountry Navigator, Samsung, and inReach are a super combination for backcountry use.  Most of the problems I have had with BCN have been me screwing up, so the best way to improve the app is to have it be more resistant to bungling users.
This app makes hiking a lot more fun. When you say the lake or stream is around the next bend, it is.

I don't know enough about Android's inner workings to comment in detail, but the sequence of events is replicable:  you download a fairly large area, the tile files increase, Android is brought to it's knees.....  Also, one more little rant:  I have been unable to discover/confirm what areas/levels of detail have been cached except by turning off WiFi and browsing around waiting for the dreaded "X X X X" to show up.  I got to that realization via an unpleasant surprise when I was out on the road and tried to look at a map.  Thought it had it downloaded.... but I was wrong.

This is not a mature product and it isn't quite worth $10 (yet).  There is a lot of screen refreshing going on, causing the map to flicker when panning with your finger.  When changing zoom levels it is quite common to see your tracks or waypoints being drawn in a different state or in the middle of the water before they are updated.  Track names are written along the contour of a track, which if you track has a lot of points causes the track name to look like a bunch of scribbles because the letters are on top of each other.  The GUI is cumbersome and not intuitive.  Some of the GUI elements look clearly like mistakes, i.e. a radio button drawn in the middle of a spinner (drop down)?  To give feedback from the app you are taken to survey monkey?   It is nice that the product is in active development but it needs a LOT more work to justify being the highest priced app on my phone, and I'm guessing one of the higher priced apps on the entire Play Store.
Great topmost.

I've used this application for more than a year and have been constantly impressed by its functionality and the developer's attention to detail.  (For example, marking of map points is achieved by panning the map so a screen-center crosshair lies over the point of interest, allowing easy and precise control in the field.)  I am an avid hiker and occasional logistician for geological field camps.  I've used this application and cached map tiles for offline navigation and light geological field work many times.  Get this application if you want a powerful tool and value control over a shiny, user-friendly interface, which this serious tool does not have.
This app is the best GPS app I have ever used. Cant wait to try the offline only mode this weekend!

I've been using BN for several years and on a G-Nexus for almost a year. This app is, without a doubt, the best available for anyone serious about route-finding in the backcountry (geocaching, hiking, skiing, biking, hunting, rafting, etc). I even use it for driving dirt roads, phone mounted to windshield. But it really shines once you climb out of the vehicle. The interface is intuitive. The developer is active and responsive to user feedback, constantly improving this app and adding valuable new functionality. Free topo maps are easily downloaded in advance if you will be in a no-cell-service area. I push my tracks and waypoints back to desktop mapping software regularly without a glitch. I no longer use my Garmin GPSr because this app makes the unit redundant. If topo map navigation and tracking is important to you and you have an Android phone, buy Backcountry Navigator, money very well spent.

The ability to select and download map tiles for offline use can't be overstated.  You can put your phone into airplane mode and really save on battery in the backcountry, even with heavy use.  At least that's been my experience.  The developer's diligent updates and responsiveness to bugs continue to make this app a winner.  Phones I've used: LG Ally and Samsung Galaxy S3.

Solved by checking "AccuraTerra date scale" under Settings.  The description says it only helps in Tennessee, but.....

Like you've read, you can download multiple formats of maps. I use the ARCGIS. I blanket downloaded all of North Ga Mountains to my SD. I Kayak and take this with me to mark camps, fish'n holes, and points of interest. You can assign neat icons to the way point, and with a picture too. Then you can send all that you've collected to a friend.                                 I left my sunglasses at a camp on the river, not too far from "a road". I set its way point as my destination and b-lined to my shades. Now my $6 shades ($5 for the Berkley Shades@ Walmart & $1 for the neck strap) are at worth at least $16 (Shades+Strap+Gas) But it was fun barreling through thorns, poison ivy, and scrub to fetch them, so I won't count my time into the equation.                                  Great app, really handy, really fun, easy to use, practical.                                  Would be nice to have a desktop version that you could plot points for an up comming trip from home. Or examine data and photos from trips taken.

Running on a Samsung Xcover GTS 5690,  BCN Pro easily acquired and loaded NOAA nav charts from its internal menu for this area very quickly.  Likewise topo maps.  Both usually pan effortlessly. Takes a while to refresh in changing scales likely a fxn of processor speed and the raster file.  From power up, GPS locked on satellites in less than two minutes, about twice as long my eTrex vista HCx.  The view of statisitics, time, distance, elevation etc. has the basics well set forth, though the screen is difficult to see in full sunlight.  Lat and lon match the etrex to 0.01 minute, accuracy runs ~8-12m compared to etrex ~3-4m, elevation reads lower than mean Columbia River Bonneville Pool level (the etrex reads higher). Also includes max slope encountered, starting and max elevation.  Neat.   Even though it seems to lack velocity made good (something small boat sailors fret about), the very fair price and map availability made this one a no brainer for my use. BCN also offers other free maps for North America and elsewhere on our planet. Pretty good for only $10. Still and yet, I carry paper maps and charts and a Suunto compass for backup. They do not depend on batteries.
Been using it for a long long time, and it just gets better. Dev is always supporting it. Just get it! You won't be disappointed.

Great app.  Also developer is quick to respond with support the times I've needed support.  Most times the support I needed was actually well documented but I didn't take the time to look.  :)

I use BCN out in the wilderness for fossil hunting as a volunteer for the Natural History Museum of Utah.  I only keep my Garmin around as a backup in case my phone battery gets too low.  Everyone else in the group asks about this great GPS that I'm using and the i-phone people are seriously considering switching to android so they can get this.  It is really handy to have the ability to take notes and pictures to go along with the waypoint marking so I've got everything associated with each other without having to coordinate everything when I get back to camp or home.  I also enjoy switching to different maps for different views of the area and a better idea of what an area is like.
